div.p: This library strives to be light in that it allows the author to use plain javascript without imposing a large layer of concepts that change the look and feel of JS.

There is just one main concept that the author needs to understand to effectively use this library. That is the flexible way in which Component Parameters can be specified and the ways that they can be composed from multiple sources of knowledge.

div.p: ComponentParams is a class that takes a free form array of parameters that describe an HTML Element/Component and structures it into a canonical set of parameters from which the HtmlElement can be constructed.

Typically, the base class of a UI component class hierarchy (such as the Component and Button based hierarchies included in the bg-dom library) passes its construction arguments into a ComponentParams constructor so that it can then query the instance's state to know how to create the the Html Element that corresponds to that component.
Each class in a hierarchy receives a list of arguments in its constructor and passes them through to its call to super(), optionally adding information to that list.
The final list that the most base class sees will be the composition of the parameters specified 1) by the user that constructs the object and 2) each class in the hierarcy.

div.p: Array elements have position but no name.

function arguments can be thought of as an array that the caller provides, which is optionally destructured by the function author providing a list of names to associate with the corresponding position in the argument array. The '...p' syntax lets us name some arguments in the front of the list and them the variable 'p' contains an array with additional arguments.

ComponentParams constructor will treat its entire argument list as an array of unnamed arguments. It will interpret these unamed arguments differently based on their type. Multiple arguments of the same type are composed together in a way that gives precendence to those that appear early in the argument array.

div.div:
Param Name: tagIDClasses
Shorthand for specifying
name : unique among siblings. used to navigate from parent
tagName : div, span, etc...
id : html #id
classes : css classnames
iconName : name of an icon image to lookup in the icon subsystem
label : text content
Syntax:
[<name>:][$<tagName>][#<idName>][.<class>[.<class>...]][ [<icon>][<label>]]
Note that every part is optional but if present it must be in the given order.
Note also that each part has a different character delimeter except for icon and label
which are delimeted by a leading space. Icon names must begin with 'icon-'
Examples:
"leftPanel:$div.vertical icon-help This is it"
"leftPanel:"
"$span.foo.bar"

Param Name: content
When content is an array (as is always the case for unamed array type arguments) each element in the array is interpreted as a contentSingle
The distinction between 'content' and 'contentSingle' is that if a 'contentSingle' parameter has a type 'Array', it is interpreted as the construction parameters to the prevailing default component constructor.

Param Names: defaultCB
Unamed functions are appended to the defaultCB array which typically is converted to a composite function that calls each function in the array.
How the defaultCB is used depends on the component being created. By default, the Component class assigns it to 'onclick'

Final Params
Additional params added to the start of the super args will lock in those values so that they can not be changed by classes that extend MyButton nor by the user that constructs the object.

div.div:
Pass Through Params
...p represents the parameters collected so far in the constructor chain.
Each constructor needs to pass these through to the next constructor in the hierarchy

div.div:
Default Params
Additional params added after ...p become a new default value.
These override the defaults set lower in the hierarchy but are overridded by values set higher in the hierarchy.
